00:40:29.700 --> 00:40:33.300
AUDIENCE: I really liked
what you said about trust.

00:40:33.300 --> 00:40:35.870
And one of the points
that I believe you made

00:40:35.870 --> 00:40:40.080
was that one of the reasons
why that trust in the sharing

00:40:40.080 --> 00:40:41.950
economy is so high
is because people

00:40:41.950 --> 00:40:44.840
are able to learn from other
people's past experiences

00:40:44.840 --> 00:40:48.070
and read reviews and
these sorts of things.

00:40:48.070 --> 00:40:54.050
But one question that I have is
that institutions and resources

00:40:54.050 --> 00:40:56.670
determined by public
opinion really

00:40:56.670 --> 00:40:57.960
isn't that new of a thing.

00:40:57.960 --> 00:41:01.630
If you think about even
voting in government,

00:41:01.630 --> 00:41:04.810
most officials are
elected by the public.

00:41:04.810 --> 00:41:08.160
And people are well aware
that those decisions are

00:41:08.160 --> 00:41:11.370
made based on public opinion.

00:41:11.370 --> 00:41:15.620
And yet, trust in
politicians is extremely low.

00:41:15.620 --> 00:41:20.210
So, really, the kind of trust
that exists within the sharing

00:41:20.210 --> 00:41:24.810
economy is somewhat new and
revolutionary, and possibly

00:41:24.810 --> 00:41:26.860
even quite an exception.

00:41:26.860 --> 00:41:29.960
I was wondering what you feel
has happened within the sharing

00:41:29.960 --> 00:41:32.590
economy that has made that
trust succeed in a way

00:41:32.590 --> 00:41:35.380
that it hasn't in the past.

00:41:35.380 --> 00:41:38.880
ARUN SUNDARARAJAN:
That's a great question.

00:41:38.880 --> 00:41:42.150
I think the ways in
which we could come up

00:41:42.150 --> 00:41:45.420
with crowd-based
decisions in the past

00:41:45.420 --> 00:41:49.400
have been at a very coarse
level of granularity.

00:41:49.400 --> 00:41:55.940
It hasn't been possible
to delegate responsibility

00:41:55.940 --> 00:42:02.160
for collectively making a
decision on small decisions

00:42:02.160 --> 00:42:05.670
to a group of
interested stakeholders

00:42:05.670 --> 00:42:10.360
because the process of running
an election is expensive.

00:42:10.360 --> 00:42:13.690
And so the big decisions, like
who should run the government

00:42:13.690 --> 00:42:16.950
or who should be my
elected representative

00:42:16.950 --> 00:42:20.400
have been determined by voting.

00:42:20.400 --> 00:42:22.960
But a vast majority of
other decisions have not.

00:42:22.960 --> 00:42:28.330
And so now with the ability
to capture information

00:42:28.330 --> 00:42:31.660
from people who have an
interest either because they

00:42:31.660 --> 00:42:34.890
have participated
in some process,

00:42:34.890 --> 00:42:38.590
they have been customers of a
particular business, the costs

00:42:38.590 --> 00:42:42.660
of collecting that information
have dropped dramatically

00:42:42.660 --> 00:42:48.130
to the point where it is now
cost-feasible to have detailed,

00:42:48.130 --> 00:42:52.360
granular feedback about every
restaurant, about every hotel,

00:42:52.360 --> 00:42:58.360
about every nail salon,
about every small business.

00:42:58.360 --> 00:43:04.600
And so given that we have
that kind of information,

00:43:04.600 --> 00:43:09.770
the way in which we
collect this feedback

00:43:09.770 --> 00:43:15.850
is naturally aligned
with interested parties

00:43:15.850 --> 00:43:18.860
contributing information.

00:43:18.860 --> 00:43:21.730
And so I think part of
the reason why there's

00:43:21.730 --> 00:43:25.470
a higher level of peer-to-peer
trust in the sharing economy

00:43:25.470 --> 00:43:29.460
than from, say,
population-scale voting systems

00:43:29.460 --> 00:43:31.960
is that it's more
specific to something

00:43:31.960 --> 00:43:34.380
that you are interested in.

00:43:34.380 --> 00:43:38.450
And the participation is also
from people whose incentives

00:43:38.450 --> 00:43:43.100
are aligned, who actually
are informed about the thing

00:43:43.100 --> 00:43:47.250
that they are providing feedback
on rather than randomly being

00:43:47.250 --> 00:43:51.837
asked to make a choice of
pretty coarse granularity.

00:43:51.837 --> 00:43:52.712
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:43:54.792 --> 00:43:56.000
ARUN SUNDARARAJAN: All right.

00:43:56.000 --> 00:43:58.800
So the question was you focused
on the successes, what have

00:43:58.800 --> 00:44:01.320
we learned from the failures?

00:44:01.320 --> 00:44:02.640
I'll answer that in two ways.

00:44:02.640 --> 00:44:05.240
First is to say that there are
certain industries that I don't

00:44:05.240 --> 00:44:07.700
think will make the transition
to crowd-based capitalism

00:44:07.700 --> 00:44:10.710
any time soon, like
high-end health care,

00:44:10.710 --> 00:44:14.010
meaning complex, health
care-- open heart surgery,

00:44:14.010 --> 00:44:16.580
unlikely to be a crowd-based
platform for that.

00:44:16.580 --> 00:44:19.230
I wouldn't use it if
there was one, for sure.

00:44:19.230 --> 00:44:21.307
On the other hand, I
cut my finger cooking.

00:44:21.307 --> 00:44:22.765
And I need someone
to stitch it up.

00:44:22.765 --> 00:44:24.850
I can certainly see a
crowd-based platform

00:44:24.850 --> 00:44:27.900
where registered nurses who
live in the neighborhood

00:44:27.900 --> 00:44:30.450
come and provide that for
a couple hundred dollars,

00:44:30.450 --> 00:44:32.220
once the trust gets
to the level where

00:44:32.220 --> 00:44:34.190
we can delegate health
care responsibility

00:44:34.190 --> 00:44:36.680
to a registered provider.

00:44:36.680 --> 00:44:38.920
So there are certain
industry segments,

00:44:38.920 --> 00:44:40.770
like heavy manufacturing,
those things

00:44:40.770 --> 00:44:44.450
are likely to maintain
their industrial capitalism

00:44:44.450 --> 00:44:46.580
structure.

00:44:46.580 --> 00:44:48.860
There've also been a
number of platforms

00:44:48.860 --> 00:44:52.830
in the sharing economy that
have started and then shut down.

00:44:52.830 --> 00:44:56.340
Some of them are just
because of VC enthusiasm.

00:44:56.340 --> 00:44:58.380
There's a lot of
money sloshing in.

00:44:58.380 --> 00:44:59.750
Bad ideas will get funded.

00:44:59.750 --> 00:45:02.390
It's the part of the process
of creative destruction.

00:45:02.390 --> 00:45:04.700
I think some of
the platforms, you

00:45:04.700 --> 00:45:07.560
have to get to-- there's a
distinction, for example,

00:45:07.560 --> 00:45:10.840
between offering
something on demand,

00:45:10.840 --> 00:45:13.220
instantly-- you place
the order and it

00:45:13.220 --> 00:45:16.710
comes to you-- versus
offering something

00:45:16.710 --> 00:45:18.080
as a scheduled service.

00:45:18.080 --> 00:45:19.540
I think we're
starting to realize

00:45:19.540 --> 00:45:23.920
that some services-- on-demand
laundry, for example-- lend

00:45:23.920 --> 00:45:26.430
themselves better to
the scheduled approach

00:45:26.430 --> 00:45:28.806
rather than I ask
you to pick it up.

00:45:28.806 --> 00:45:30.430
And you come and pick
it up in an hour,

00:45:30.430 --> 00:45:33.209
where the logistics start
to become more complicated.

00:45:33.209 --> 00:45:35.250
I think one of the things
we've learned from some

00:45:35.250 --> 00:45:40.150
of the failures is that you
need a certain immense-- just

00:45:40.150 --> 00:45:43.130
because Uber and Lyft are
successful with the on-demand,

00:45:43.130 --> 00:45:47.070
instantaneous model doesn't mean
that every other industry needs

00:45:47.070 --> 00:45:48.030
that.

00:45:48.030 --> 00:45:50.290
If I want a ride, I
want it right now.

00:45:50.290 --> 00:45:52.090
And I want it in three minutes.

00:45:52.090 --> 00:45:56.650
But if I want my laundry done,
or I want dinner this evening,

00:45:56.650 --> 00:45:58.870
it's quite feasible that
the successful model

00:45:58.870 --> 00:46:01.780
is going to be one where instead
of saying I want it now, bring

00:46:01.780 --> 00:46:03.960
it to me, you might
say in the morning,

00:46:03.960 --> 00:46:06.520
well, this is what I want,
and I want it at 7:00 o'clock,

00:46:06.520 --> 00:46:09.860
or come and pick it up
at 3:00 in the afternoon.

00:46:09.860 --> 00:46:13.415
And those models may
end up dominating.

00:46:13.415 --> 00:46:14.790
I guess what else
have we learned

00:46:14.790 --> 00:46:15.960
from some of the failures?

00:46:15.960 --> 00:46:19.890
Well, there've been
a number of attempts

00:46:19.890 --> 00:46:22.980
to create peer-to-peer
rental markets for assets

00:46:22.980 --> 00:46:26.080
other than cars and
space in your home.

00:46:26.080 --> 00:46:28.660
If you think about it, space
in your home and your car

00:46:28.660 --> 00:46:31.170
are the two typically
most valuable

00:46:31.170 --> 00:46:34.250
assets an individual has.

00:46:34.250 --> 00:46:36.150
The home is utilized
at a high level,

00:46:36.150 --> 00:46:39.810
but it's so valuable relative
to a person's typical income

00:46:39.810 --> 00:46:42.400
that even a small
amount of slack

00:46:42.400 --> 00:46:44.180
can overcome the
transaction costs,

00:46:44.180 --> 00:46:45.730
and you've got a
market like Airbnb.

00:46:45.730 --> 00:46:49.060
A car is underutilized
vastly, and so

00:46:49.060 --> 00:46:50.560
peer-to-peer rental
markets work.

00:46:50.560 --> 00:46:52.880
But they haven't worked for
things like vacuum cleaners

00:46:52.880 --> 00:46:56.460
and power drills and all of
these celebrated 2012 sharing

00:46:56.460 --> 00:46:57.721
economy examples.

00:46:57.721 --> 00:46:59.970
I think what's happening
there is that the transaction

00:46:59.970 --> 00:47:01.860
costs are still too high.

00:47:01.860 --> 00:47:05.480
The value that is created
from lending clothing--

00:47:05.480 --> 00:47:10.040
every city I've gone to has a
peer-to-peer clothing rental

00:47:10.040 --> 00:47:13.540
market that is struggling
with logistics.

00:47:13.540 --> 00:47:15.360
So I think once we
get to the point

00:47:15.360 --> 00:47:18.710
where the objects
that we're sharing

00:47:18.710 --> 00:47:22.920
are self-aware-- the
digitization of the physical--

00:47:22.920 --> 00:47:24.900
an object knows where it is.

00:47:24.900 --> 00:47:26.850
It knows how much
it's being used.

00:47:26.850 --> 00:47:29.260
And it can call on
transport, if needed.

00:47:29.260 --> 00:47:31.580
And so if there's a drone
delivery network that

00:47:31.580 --> 00:47:33.620
can pick it up and
take it, then you're

00:47:33.620 --> 00:47:35.700
going to lower the
transaction costs to the point

00:47:35.700 --> 00:47:39.290
where a lot more peer-to-peer
rental markets will

00:47:39.290 --> 00:47:42.505
become feasible for
lower value assets.

00:47:42.505 --> 00:47:44.880
I think about this, and I
think about the only thing more

00:47:44.880 --> 00:47:48.750
frightening than a network
of drones flying above me

00:47:48.750 --> 00:47:53.040
is if they're carrying
power drills as well.

00:47:53.040 --> 00:47:55.080
So it may not be the power
drills that start it,

00:47:55.080 --> 00:47:59.410
maybe the $500 dress that you
want to rent from someone.

00:47:59.410 --> 00:48:00.910
I think those are
some of the things

00:48:00.910 --> 00:48:02.400
that we've learned from
some of the failures,

00:48:02.400 --> 00:48:03.816
that the transaction
costs are too

00:48:03.816 --> 00:48:06.690
high for certain peer-to-peer,
and that on-demand may not

00:48:06.690 --> 00:48:07.470
be instantaneous.

00:48:07.470 --> 00:48:10.690
On-demand may not be-- unit
economics may not work out,

00:48:10.690 --> 00:48:14.880
but a scheduled
model may work well.

00:48:14.880 --> 00:48:17.030
Well, I don't have
a good answer.

00:48:17.030 --> 00:48:19.380
So the question was, we
had a high level of trust

00:48:19.380 --> 00:48:21.570
in the 1950s.

00:48:21.570 --> 00:48:24.310
In the United States,
people would hitchhike.

00:48:24.310 --> 00:48:27.330
That trust level
seems to have dropped.

00:48:27.330 --> 00:48:28.240
What happened?

00:48:28.240 --> 00:48:30.400
And will we see a
similar drop-off

00:48:30.400 --> 00:48:33.960
in trust in the sharing economy
as it gets more commonplace?

00:48:33.960 --> 00:48:36.520
So I don't know why
trust has dropped off

00:48:36.520 --> 00:48:41.390
so much in especially the US
economy over the last 40 years.

00:48:41.390 --> 00:48:44.830
I've been tracking these numbers
from the General Social Survey.

00:48:44.830 --> 00:48:46.850
They ask people as part
of that [INAUDIBLE].

00:48:46.850 --> 00:48:49.350
Every year or two years,
they have the giant survey

00:48:49.350 --> 00:48:53.130
about everything from like
gun control to choice.

00:48:53.130 --> 00:48:54.860
And one of the
questions they ask

00:48:54.860 --> 00:48:58.210
is, in general, you feel
people can be trusted

00:48:58.210 --> 00:48:59.990
or you can't be too careful.

00:48:59.990 --> 00:49:03.080
And the response is
a reliable metric

00:49:03.080 --> 00:49:06.100
that we've got 40 years of
data about the level of trust

00:49:06.100 --> 00:49:07.930
in society.

00:49:07.930 --> 00:49:12.240
So I've seen that number fall
from about 50% in the mid '70s

00:49:12.240 --> 00:49:14.590
to about 30% today.

00:49:14.590 --> 00:49:16.710
So our level of trust in
other people, in general,

00:49:16.710 --> 00:49:17.780
has gone down.

00:49:17.780 --> 00:49:22.250
The fall has been steepest
among people under the age of 35

00:49:22.250 --> 00:49:25.420
where less than one in five
people under the age of 35

00:49:25.420 --> 00:49:28.470
today believe that other
people are trustworthy.

00:49:28.470 --> 00:49:32.950
The thing is that in parallel
with this fall in general trust

00:49:32.950 --> 00:49:36.210
has been an increase in
digitally mediated trust.

00:49:36.210 --> 00:49:40.010
We're getting more accustomed
to reading digital cues

00:49:40.010 --> 00:49:42.120
because we're growing
up reading Yelp reviews,

00:49:42.120 --> 00:49:45.430
reading Amazon reviews,
understanding what's real

00:49:45.430 --> 00:49:48.560
and what's fake about a
Facebook or LinkedIn network.

00:49:48.560 --> 00:49:50.610
And so our ability
to make assessments

00:49:50.610 --> 00:49:54.230
about someone else based on
digital information about them

00:49:54.230 --> 00:49:56.330
is getting more sophisticated.

00:49:56.330 --> 00:49:58.540
And that's part
of the reason why

00:49:58.540 --> 00:50:02.900
when although the average
person will definitely not

00:50:02.900 --> 00:50:06.210
hitchhike in the United
States, it's likely

00:50:06.210 --> 00:50:10.550
that as city to city
car-sharing comes along,

00:50:10.550 --> 00:50:12.530
people will participate in it.

00:50:12.530 --> 00:50:14.080
Or the average
person wouldn't stand

00:50:14.080 --> 00:50:16.204
on the side of the road in
France and hitch a ride,

00:50:16.204 --> 00:50:19.280
but they would trust the
person on BlaBlaCar enough.

00:50:19.280 --> 00:50:21.420
Will this trust
dissolve over time?

00:50:21.420 --> 00:50:22.210
I hope not.

00:50:24.820 --> 00:50:28.360
I think that an alternative
path that it could take

00:50:28.360 --> 00:50:30.900
is that it could raise
the general level of trust

00:50:30.900 --> 00:50:35.360
in society because more and
more of our everyday economic

00:50:35.360 --> 00:50:38.160
activities are going to be
taking that leap of trust

00:50:38.160 --> 00:50:40.110
with someone we don't know.

00:50:40.110 --> 00:50:43.510
The vast majority of these
are positive experiences.

00:50:43.510 --> 00:50:47.100
And so, as we get accustomed,
as we stop buying from brands

00:50:47.100 --> 00:50:50.230
and start to get our rides,
our food, our accommodation

00:50:50.230 --> 00:50:53.000
from other people, and
as these end up being

00:50:53.000 --> 00:50:55.200
positive experiences,
this may start

00:50:55.200 --> 00:50:58.750
to inject a greater
level of general trust

00:50:58.750 --> 00:51:00.290
in society because
we'll discover

00:51:00.290 --> 00:51:03.410
through our own experience
that most people are,

00:51:03.410 --> 00:51:05.590
in general, trustworthy.

00:51:05.590 --> 00:51:09.950
And now that we also have
these digital feedback systems,

00:51:09.950 --> 00:51:13.460
it raises the bar for
behavior, as well.

00:51:13.460 --> 00:51:21.000
Because if you were running a--
if you were, say, selling food

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:24.250
to your community in
the past and someone

00:51:24.250 --> 00:51:27.710
had a bad experience, maybe
they'll tell their friends.

00:51:27.710 --> 00:51:32.450
But it's not going to permeate
across your entire demand base.

00:51:32.450 --> 00:51:34.920
Today if you're selling
food through Josephine

00:51:34.920 --> 00:51:38.890
and someone gets food
poisoning, the entire community

00:51:38.890 --> 00:51:41.330
is going to know instantly
through your feedback.

00:51:41.330 --> 00:51:42.950
And that will shutter
your business.

00:51:42.950 --> 00:51:46.140
So it raises the bar
on you to behave,

00:51:46.140 --> 00:51:49.281
take actions that
are more trustworthy.

00:51:49.281 --> 00:51:52.426
AUDIENCE: So how do you see
the long-term [INAUDIBLE]?

00:51:52.426 --> 00:51:54.300
ARUN SUNDARARAJAN: Well,
to the second point,

00:51:54.300 --> 00:51:59.500
it seems likely that there
will be some things-- there

00:51:59.500 --> 00:52:02.130
are some people who stay in
an Airbnb because they say,

00:52:02.130 --> 00:52:02.810
oh, it's cool.

00:52:02.810 --> 00:52:03.480
It's different.

00:52:03.480 --> 00:52:05.420
It's not what my parents did.

00:52:05.420 --> 00:52:08.720
But Airbnb is
becoming, for example,

00:52:08.720 --> 00:52:13.599
increasingly the
preferred solution

00:52:13.599 --> 00:52:14.640
for more and more people.

00:52:14.640 --> 00:52:17.410
It's not quite there yet
for business travelers.

00:52:17.410 --> 00:52:19.390
But for people who
are taking a vacation,

00:52:19.390 --> 00:52:23.339
it's not so much about it
being cool and fringe anymore.

00:52:23.339 --> 00:52:24.880
I mean, they are
the biggest provider

00:52:24.880 --> 00:52:26.940
of short-term accommodation
in the world now.

00:52:26.940 --> 00:52:30.900
So it's no longer
a fringe activity.

00:52:30.900 --> 00:52:35.580
I think that kind of model will
persist because it will just

00:52:35.580 --> 00:52:37.760
become normal.

00:52:37.760 --> 00:52:39.500
It enters the cultural dialogue.

00:52:39.500 --> 00:52:42.110
It becomes the way in which
you find accommodation.

00:52:42.110 --> 00:52:44.830
You don't think twice about
staying in a hotel now.

00:52:44.830 --> 00:52:46.360
It's just the thing
that you do when

00:52:46.360 --> 00:52:48.250
you travel to another city.

00:52:48.250 --> 00:52:50.400
And so I don't think the
acceptance or rejection

00:52:50.400 --> 00:52:54.410
of Airbnb in a decade is going
to be colored by, is this cool?

00:52:54.410 --> 00:52:55.214
Or, is this fringe?

00:52:55.214 --> 00:52:55.880
Or, is this not?

00:52:55.880 --> 00:53:00.180
It'll just be the way in
which you find accommodation.

00:53:00.180 --> 00:53:03.730
To the economic
factors, well, that's

00:53:03.730 --> 00:53:06.690
an industry by
industry question.

00:53:06.690 --> 00:53:09.470
The unit economics
associated with Airbnb

00:53:09.470 --> 00:53:13.540
are fundamentally superior to
those of the hotel industry

00:53:13.540 --> 00:53:18.820
because you are tapping
into excess capacity.

00:53:18.820 --> 00:53:23.630
And so the unit economics
of peer-to-peer car rental

00:53:23.630 --> 00:53:26.670
are fundamentally
superior to that of Hertz

00:53:26.670 --> 00:53:31.720
because Getaround now has more
members in the San Francisco

00:53:31.720 --> 00:53:34.360
Bay area than Zipcar.

00:53:34.360 --> 00:53:36.710
They've done it in an
extremely short period of time.

00:53:36.710 --> 00:53:39.960
And this is not
Uber-level funding.

00:53:39.960 --> 00:53:44.250
They're a modest-sized company,
but they're already that big.

00:53:44.250 --> 00:53:46.250
How are they able
to scale so rapidly?

00:53:46.250 --> 00:53:48.550
Well, because scaling
there involves

00:53:48.550 --> 00:53:52.580
tapping into existing cars,
not leasing a fleet of cars

00:53:52.580 --> 00:53:53.770
yourself.

00:53:53.770 --> 00:53:55.920
So I'm optimistic
about many slices

00:53:55.920 --> 00:53:58.410
of crowd-based capitalism
here because the underlying

00:53:58.410 --> 00:54:02.090
economics are just
fundamentally superior.

00:54:02.090 --> 00:54:03.890
I think most of the
subsidies that we've

00:54:03.890 --> 00:54:05.820
seen from venture
money have been

00:54:05.820 --> 00:54:07.560
in the point-to-point
transportation

00:54:07.560 --> 00:54:11.080
space, the ride-sharing space.

00:54:11.080 --> 00:54:13.126
Over there, we've got
another transition

00:54:13.126 --> 00:54:14.500
that's coming that
all of you are

00:54:14.500 --> 00:54:18.860
familiar with, the autonomous
vehicle transition.

00:54:18.860 --> 00:54:22.490
And that will take
longer than, I think,

00:54:22.490 --> 00:54:25.210
Uber and Lyft
think it will take.

00:54:25.210 --> 00:54:28.060
I don't expect that we will
have autonomous vehicles that

00:54:28.060 --> 00:54:32.000
are mass market and
widespread in five years.

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:33.376
I'm sure the
technology is ready,

00:54:33.376 --> 00:54:34.791
but there's a
cultural acceptance.

00:54:34.791 --> 00:54:36.270
There's a regulatory acceptance.

00:54:36.270 --> 00:54:38.300
There's an interaction
between the autonomous

00:54:38.300 --> 00:54:39.600
and the non-autonomous.

00:54:39.600 --> 00:54:41.390
All of these need
to be ironed out.

00:54:41.390 --> 00:54:43.930
And it's mostly the
acceptance factor.

00:54:43.930 --> 00:54:45.660
But those start to come in.

00:54:45.660 --> 00:54:48.210
And so as these
subsidies start to phase,

00:54:48.210 --> 00:54:52.150
the cost structure will
start to improve to the point

00:54:52.150 --> 00:54:56.740
where, for an increasing
fraction of the population,

00:54:56.740 --> 00:55:00.040
on-demand transportation
will be as economical or more

00:55:00.040 --> 00:55:02.560
economical than buying a car.

00:55:02.560 --> 00:55:04.560
I mean, right now
it's the case for me.

00:55:04.560 --> 00:55:06.240
I live in Manhattan.

00:55:06.240 --> 00:55:09.800
75% of us don't own cars
anyway because owning

00:55:09.800 --> 00:55:11.470
a car is just useless.

00:55:11.470 --> 00:55:13.490
You can't find parking.

00:55:13.490 --> 00:55:14.730
It's really expensive.

00:55:14.730 --> 00:55:16.550
And so you use subway.

00:55:16.550 --> 00:55:17.150
You use taxi.

00:55:17.150 --> 00:55:19.420
You use on-demand
transportation.

00:55:19.420 --> 00:55:24.090
And you have similar, like San
Francisco, LA, the big cities.

00:55:24.090 --> 00:55:26.770
But at least half the
population of the US

00:55:26.770 --> 00:55:28.850
lives in a densely
enough populated area

00:55:28.850 --> 00:55:33.430
where if the costs fall enough,
the on-demand alternative

00:55:33.430 --> 00:55:37.297
will be cost comparable
to owning your own car.

00:55:37.297 --> 00:55:39.630
And so if you think about
that, you think about the fact

00:55:39.630 --> 00:55:42.460
that Americans spend
over a trillion dollars

00:55:42.460 --> 00:55:44.740
every year buying new and
used cars-- just buying,

00:55:44.740 --> 00:55:47.660
forget about maintenance
and all of that.

00:55:47.660 --> 00:55:50.320
So what the investors
in Lyft and Uber

00:55:50.320 --> 00:55:52.050
and there are for
others-- Go-Jek

00:55:52.050 --> 00:55:58.480
in Indonesia, Grab in
Singapore, Didi Chuxing

00:55:58.480 --> 00:56:02.610
in China, Ola in India--
all of them are unicorns.

00:56:02.610 --> 00:56:04.820
But what the VCs are betting
on isn't that these guys

00:56:04.820 --> 00:56:06.010
will be the new taxi.

00:56:06.010 --> 00:56:07.509
What they're betting
on is that they

00:56:07.509 --> 00:56:10.120
will capture a slice of
the trillions of dollars

00:56:10.120 --> 00:56:12.010
that people spend
buying cars every year.

00:56:12.010 --> 00:56:14.431
So if you capture
5% of that trillion,

00:56:14.431 --> 00:56:15.805
you've justified
your valuations.

00:56:15.805 --> 00:56:21.860
So over there, I think
the model will work,

00:56:21.860 --> 00:56:26.800
but it'll expand dramatically
as the unit economics improve

00:56:26.800 --> 00:56:29.797
because of automation.

00:56:29.797 --> 00:56:31.380
Well, there's one
more point, as well.

00:56:31.380 --> 00:56:34.560
Because of automation, but
before that, because also that

00:56:34.560 --> 00:56:37.640
you have gotten
enough of a density

00:56:37.640 --> 00:56:40.130
where genuine carpooling
through a market

00:56:40.130 --> 00:56:42.220
starts to become possible.

00:56:42.220 --> 00:56:45.010
And so you've got people driving
from San Francisco to Mountain

00:56:45.010 --> 00:56:47.250
View and then driving back from
Mountain View to San Francisco.

00:56:47.250 --> 00:56:48.749
Even today, you
look at the highway.

00:56:48.749 --> 00:56:49.870
Most people have one car.

00:56:49.870 --> 00:56:51.680
Most cars have one person.

00:56:51.680 --> 00:56:55.380
If you get enough of a density
in a market where you can start

00:56:55.380 --> 00:56:56.990
to get people to
share that space,

00:56:56.990 --> 00:56:59.410
then that model starts
to become viable.

00:56:59.410 --> 00:57:02.290
And so that's another thing that
will drive down unit economics.

00:57:02.290 --> 00:57:04.710
But I'm not making a
living driving the car.

00:57:04.710 --> 00:57:08.090
I happen to be driving it from
one place to another anyway.

00:57:08.090 --> 00:57:10.320
And I'm just making
some extra money

00:57:10.320 --> 00:57:13.480
by having someone else
subsidizing my costs.

00:57:13.480 --> 00:57:14.890
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:57:14.890 --> 00:57:18.450
ARUN SUNDARARAJAN: Well, I can't
quantify how much of a reason--

00:57:18.450 --> 00:57:22.880
so the question was,
I argued that part

00:57:22.880 --> 00:57:26.090
of the reason why someone would
become a driver on BlaBlaCar

00:57:26.090 --> 00:57:28.590
is social reasons.

00:57:28.590 --> 00:57:30.940
To what extent is this
a convincing reason

00:57:30.940 --> 00:57:35.590
and how much is a similar reason
present in other industries

00:57:35.590 --> 00:57:37.990
in the sharing economy?

00:57:37.990 --> 00:57:40.640
My conversations
with BlaBlaCar have

00:57:40.640 --> 00:57:43.100
suggested that this
is a big part of why

00:57:43.100 --> 00:57:46.190
people supply on BlaBlaCar.

00:57:46.190 --> 00:57:49.378
You get lonely traveling a
long distance by yourself.

00:57:49.378 --> 00:57:51.127
It's nice to have other
people in the car.

00:57:55.010 --> 00:57:58.770
It seems that, on average,
we live in a society

00:57:58.770 --> 00:58:02.850
where people have insufficient
connection with other people.

00:58:02.850 --> 00:58:04.440
There's a lot of
research that has

00:58:04.440 --> 00:58:09.020
suggested that, physiologically,
we need social connection.

00:58:09.020 --> 00:58:11.970
There's something
analogous to physical pain

00:58:11.970 --> 00:58:14.590
that lights up in
your neural network

00:58:14.590 --> 00:58:16.710
when you don't have
enough social connection.

00:58:16.710 --> 00:58:18.730
Neurologists call
it social pain.

00:58:18.730 --> 00:58:20.990
So that's certainly
part of it that

00:58:20.990 --> 00:58:23.700
would cause you to make
a decision that just

00:58:23.700 --> 00:58:26.740
purely on the economic
aspects isn't something

00:58:26.740 --> 00:58:28.290
that you'd be drawn to.

00:58:28.290 --> 00:58:31.330
So it's a combination
of reasons.

00:58:31.330 --> 00:58:34.140
I think a lot of
recent Airbnb hosts--

00:58:34.140 --> 00:58:37.610
the fastest rate of
growth in Airbnb hosting

00:58:37.610 --> 00:58:40.600
tends to be in not the
millennial demographic,

00:58:40.600 --> 00:58:43.050
but in the over 50 demographic.

00:58:43.050 --> 00:58:46.900
And I think over there, empty
nests, and I have spare space,

00:58:46.900 --> 00:58:49.780
and it'll be nice to have
people staying in my home also

00:58:49.780 --> 00:58:53.710
plays a role that is
operating in conjunction with,

00:58:53.710 --> 00:58:55.180
OK, I can trust
this person enough

00:58:55.180 --> 00:58:57.660
and I make some money as well.

00:58:57.660 --> 00:59:00.770
So I don't think that
it's the only reason.

00:59:00.770 --> 00:59:03.020
Well, the one place where
it's the only reason

00:59:03.020 --> 00:59:04.960
is with couch surfing.

00:59:04.960 --> 00:59:06.640
Couch surfing is a
platform that allows

00:59:06.640 --> 00:59:08.431
you to sleep on someone's
couch in exchange

00:59:08.431 --> 00:59:11.250
for letting them sleep on your--
or people sleep on your couch.

00:59:11.250 --> 00:59:15.360
But there's no money there
because couch surfing is not

00:59:15.360 --> 00:59:17.750
really a marketplace.

00:59:17.750 --> 00:59:19.250
It's a social network.

00:59:19.250 --> 00:59:22.150
The typical couch-surfing person
goes to a new city and says,

00:59:22.150 --> 00:59:23.200
where's the party?

00:59:23.200 --> 00:59:25.690
It's not like, I
need a place to stay.

00:59:25.690 --> 00:59:30.210
It's a pure gift economy in that
the exchange of accommodation

00:59:30.210 --> 00:59:34.690
is purely incidental,
and the real objective

00:59:34.690 --> 00:59:36.270
is to build the connection.

00:59:36.270 --> 00:59:39.040
So over there, the social
reason is dominant.

00:59:39.040 --> 00:59:43.470
But in other situations, it's
a combination of factors.

00:59:43.470 --> 00:59:46.670
Well, I mean, you
certainly have a point

00:59:46.670 --> 00:59:49.060
with-- so the
question was, there

00:59:49.060 --> 00:59:52.080
are a couple of conjectures
that are given about why there's

00:59:52.080 --> 00:59:57.100
been a drop in societal
trust over the last 50 years.

00:59:57.100 --> 01:00:02.300
One is the sensationalization
by the media of negative events

01:00:02.300 --> 01:00:04.230
with increasing intensity.

01:00:04.230 --> 01:00:07.310
And the other is, I guess,
flawed regulatory intervention

01:00:07.310 --> 01:00:11.010
and reaction to bad
events that have

01:00:11.010 --> 01:00:14.760
suppressed certain things that
would have otherwise proceeded

01:00:14.760 --> 01:00:16.960
well.

01:00:16.960 --> 01:00:19.580
I mean, both are possibilities.

01:00:19.580 --> 01:00:26.760
I certainly think that if you
look at the level of trust

01:00:26.760 --> 01:00:30.760
or the level of activity
and, as a consequence,

01:00:30.760 --> 01:00:34.730
the implied level of trust that
BlaBlaCar users in the United

01:00:34.730 --> 01:00:37.940
Kingdom have, it's a little
different from the rest

01:00:37.940 --> 01:00:38.780
of Europe.

01:00:38.780 --> 01:00:41.530
And that could be attributable,
in part, to the fact

01:00:41.530 --> 01:00:46.130
that you don't have the
sensationalized "hitchhiking is

01:00:46.130 --> 01:00:49.040
dangerous" kinds of stories
in France and Germany

01:00:49.040 --> 01:00:52.070
as much as you do in
the United Kingdom.

01:00:52.070 --> 01:00:54.800
And so that's certainly
a possibility,

01:00:54.800 --> 01:00:59.610
that certain activities have
been labeled as negative

01:00:59.610 --> 01:01:03.500
because of a relatively small
number of extremely bad things

01:01:03.500 --> 01:01:05.680
that have happened.

01:01:05.680 --> 01:01:10.470
But I think that there is
something more basic that

01:01:10.470 --> 01:01:13.010
has happened when it
comes to explaining

01:01:13.010 --> 01:01:15.110
that drop of trust--
I mean, I don't

01:01:15.110 --> 01:01:20.520
know exactly what it is--
because the drop in the level

01:01:20.520 --> 01:01:23.140
of trust in society
hasn't just been

01:01:23.140 --> 01:01:26.020
on specific kinds of activities.

01:01:26.020 --> 01:01:27.820
It's been fairly
broad-based, which

01:01:27.820 --> 01:01:31.750
is why I think the sharing
economy holds so much promise

01:01:31.750 --> 01:01:33.280
of re-injecting this trust.

01:01:33.280 --> 01:01:38.400
To your second point about is it
flawed regulatory intervention?

01:01:38.400 --> 01:01:41.140
If that is the reason,
then the sharing economy

01:01:41.140 --> 01:01:46.180
is probably in better shape
because a lot of people

01:01:46.180 --> 01:01:49.920
think of these
platforms that we've

01:01:49.920 --> 01:01:53.910
talked about as somehow
making an attempt

01:01:53.910 --> 01:01:56.500
to reduce regulation.

01:01:56.500 --> 01:01:59.970
But that's actually
not the case.

01:01:59.970 --> 01:02:01.890
The changes that they're
trying to induce,

01:02:01.890 --> 01:02:04.560
or the changes that they
will induce, are different.

01:02:04.560 --> 01:02:08.120
They are a change in certain
government regulations

01:02:08.120 --> 01:02:11.520
that don't fit anymore
and actually an increase

01:02:11.520 --> 01:02:13.890
in total regulation, except
that the regulation is

01:02:13.890 --> 01:02:17.000
done by someone other
than the government.

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:19.560
And so if you think about
the amount of regulation that

01:02:19.560 --> 01:02:22.870
will be done in a crowd-based
capitalism economy,

01:02:22.870 --> 01:02:24.270
it will actually be more.

01:02:24.270 --> 01:02:27.360
It just won't all come
from the government.

01:02:27.360 --> 01:02:31.490
And where I'm getting to is
that because in some ways

01:02:31.490 --> 01:02:34.210
the equivalent to
government regulation that

01:02:34.210 --> 01:02:37.420
emerges from a
platform is targeted

01:02:37.420 --> 01:02:42.540
at solving a real problem and
is created by a crowd of people.

01:02:42.540 --> 01:02:44.550
The chances that
it will be flawed

01:02:44.550 --> 01:02:48.580
regulation that might suppress
the activity are a lot lower.

01:02:48.580 --> 01:02:51.740
I mean, it's naturally aligned
with encouraging the activity

01:02:51.740 --> 01:02:53.610
rather than discouraging it.

01:02:53.610 --> 01:02:56.860
So if your conjecture about
regulatory intervention leading

01:02:56.860 --> 01:02:59.840
to lower trust is correct,
then the sharing economy

01:02:59.840 --> 01:03:00.910
is a solution.

01:03:00.910 --> 01:03:03.146
The regulatory systems
of the sharing economy,

01:03:03.146 --> 01:03:04.270
they're more participatory.

01:03:04.270 --> 01:03:05.740
They're more ethical
in some ways.

01:03:05.740 --> 01:03:10.205
They're more targeted at
solving actual market failures.

01:03:10.205 --> 01:03:12.700
There's some promise there.

01:03:12.700 --> 01:03:13.200
All right.

01:03:13.200 --> 01:03:14.459
Thank you very much enjoy.

01:03:14.459 --> 01:03:15.500
I enjoyed the discussion.

01:03:15.500 --> 01:03:18.250
[APPLAUSE]

